      <hedline>
        <hl1>A War Over Rent, on Two Coasts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Scott Coon letter replies to Paul Krugman's June 7 Op-Ed column on rent control in San Francisco; suggests that tenants be allowed to sell their rent control rights for a market-driven lump sum, either to the landlord or to incoming tenants</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Paul Krugman diagnoses San Francisco's rent control problem, (column, June 7) but stops before recommending treatment.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Paul Krugman diagnoses San Francisco's rent control problem, (column, June 7) but stops before recommending treatment.</p>
        <p>The city granted rent-controlled tenants a share of the landlord's property rights without financially compensating the landlord, although the tenants enjoy the economic benefit of lower rents.</p>
        <p>However, the obvious solution -- repealing rent control -- would be the same bad thinking turned backward. Tenants should be allowed to sell their rent-control rights for a market-driven lump sum, either to the landlord or to incoming tenants. Rents could be raised for the new tenant, but the extra cost to them of purchasing rent-control rights would force landlords to keep rent somewhat below market levels. Over time, most rent control would be bought out of existence by landlords.</p>
        <p>SCOTT COON  San Francisco, June 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
